The hunchbacked flute player is a deity rooted deep in Anasazi traditions. His mythology is still present in the traditions of many pueblo peoples. To the Hopi, he is Kokopelli, influential in fertility and abundance, whether it be the hunt, the fields or human reproduction. This figure is representative of the symbols used by the Anasazi (The Ancient Ones).

The figures depicted on this pottery are representative of those chisled into canyon walls by the Anasazi, an ancient civilization of the desert southwest. The petroglyphs and muted geometric shapes give a glimps into the life of ancient rock artists who diappeared long ago. The shadow of their existence is cast over the centuries.
